<body>

  <p>
    The idea of 
    <span class="term">private land ownership
      <span class="popup">A system in which individuals, rather than communities, hold legal rights to land.</span>
    </span> 
    was foreign; land was held 
    <span class="term">communally
      <span class="popup">Shared by all members of a group rather than owned by individuals.</span>
    </span> 
    and worked 
    <span class="term">collectively
      <span class="popup">Done together as a group, with shared responsibility.</span>
    </span>. 
    Native Americans shared the land with each other.
  </p>

  <p>
    The largest 
    <span class="term">domesticated animals
      <span class="popup">Animals that have been tamed and bred for human use, such as food, work, or companionship.</span>
    </span> 
    were 
    <span class="term">dogs
      <span class="popup">Domesticated canines used for hunting, guarding, and companionship.</span>
    </span>, 
    <span class="term">llamas
      <span class="popup">South American animals domesticated for carrying loads and providing fiber.</span>
    </span>, 
    and 
    <span class="term">alpacas
      <span class="popup">South American animals domesticated for their soft wool, used in textiles.</span>
    </span>, 
    and therefore the Indians could not rely on such animal by-products such as 
    <span class="term">wool
      <span class="popup">A textile fiber obtained mainly from sheep and similar animals, used for clothing and fabrics.</span>
    </span>, 
    <span class="term">leather
      <span class="popup">Material made from the skin of animals, used for clothing, tools, and shelter.</span>
    </span>, 
    <span class="term">milk
      <span class="popup">A nutrient-rich liquid produced by mammals to feed their young, also used for food products.</span>
    </span>, 
    and 
    <span class="term">meat
      <span class="popup">The flesh of animals used as food.</span>
    </span>. 
    Although some societies had developed the 
    <span class="term">wheel
      <span class="popup">A circular object that rotates on an axle; used to create carts, machines, and tools.</span>
    </span>, 
    it was used as a toy. No society had shaped 
    <span class="term">metal
      <span class="popup">A solid material like copper, gold, or iron, valued for strength, durability, and ability to be shaped.</span>
    </span> 
    into 
    <span class="term">guns
      <span class="popup">Weapons that use gunpowder to fire projectiles.</span>
    </span>, 
    <span class="term">swords
      <span class="popup">Bladed weapons designed for cutting or thrusting.</span>
    </span>, 
    or 
    <span class="term">tools
      <span class="popup">Objects used to carry out tasks, such as farming, building, or crafting.</span>
    </span>; 
    none had 
    <span class="term">gunpowder
      <span class="popup">An explosive mixture used historically for firearms, fireworks, and mining.</span>
    </span>, 
    <span class="term">sailing ships
      <span class="popup">Large boats powered by sails, used for long-distance travel and trade.</span>
    </span>, 
    or 
    <span class="term">mounted warriors
      <span class="popup">Fighters on horseback, giving them speed and power in battle.</span>
    </span>.
  </p>

